Obtained a plaything. When you have obtained a
plaything, you can switch between it
using the W key and the Q key, and use
the item with the confirm button.

When you press the W key, it will switch in
the order of bare hands -> tool 1 ->
tool 2 -> tool 3 -> bare hands. In the
case of the Q key, it will be the
opposite.

You can catch bugs by using a bug net for
insects and a fishing rod for fish,
depending on the target. However, you
cannot use playthings like these inside
the house.

Furthermore, please note that you cannot talk to or
examine things while holding a tool. You
can confirm the above explanation in the
instruction manual as well.

Let's quickly grab the 'bug net' and try
catching the 'bugs' flying around or
perched on trees.

\N<Boy>If you swing a bug net towards bugs, you
can catch them. Bugs are small, so
search carefully. They might be flying
around or shining black on trees.

\N<Boy>Oh? Did you catch a sawtooth stag beetle?
Then let's have a bug battle right away!
\N<Boku>Um... How do you play bug battles?

\N<Boy>Hmm... Listen carefully, the basics of bug
battles are like a one-on-one rock-
paper-scissors game.

\N<Boy>That's right, rock-paper-scissors. There are
four commands you can give to bugs.
Attack, special move, barrier, and
charge.

\N<Boku>Huh? Barrier...? Can bugs really do
something like that...?

\N<Boy>Use your imagination there. You play
pretend games, right? Even in a game of
tag, can you really become the demon?

\N<Boy>If you understand, then let's continue
with the explanation.

\N<Boy>First, attacks are strong against barriers,
but weak against special moves.

\N<Boy>Finishing moves are strong against attacks, but
weak against barriers.

\N<Boy>Barriers are strong against finishing moves, but
weak against attacks.

\N<Boy>And finally, Charge is weak against
everything, but it slightly restores the
bug's stamina and increases its attack
power for the next turn.

\N<Boy>What you need to be careful of is that
finishing moves require 'move points'
and can't be used when they run out.

\N<Boy>Also, you can't give the same command twice
in a row.

\N<Boy>This rule applies to both you and your
opponent, so think carefully about what
the opponent will do next and give
instructions to the bug.

\N<Boy>The one who reduces the opponent's bug's HP
to zero first wins. Also, if the bug
moves back due to an 'attack' or
'finishing move', falling off the dohyo
(sumo ring) counts as a loss.

\N<Boy>Well, it would be faster to actually do it.
Don't worry, I'll go easy on you.

\N<Boy>Oh, don't forget that the bug at the front
of your team will participate in the
battle. Well then, let's get started
quickly.

\N<Boy>Well, I guess there's no helping it. Listen
carefully.

During the Bug Battle, you can change the
speed of the Bug Battle by pressing the
Shift key. When in Speed Up mode, a
music note symbol will be displayed in
the upper left corner.
